The farmer has five sugar apple, 13 atemoya, eight soursop (graviola) , 14 custard apple and five jackfruit trees.He sourced the seedlings from Kenya Agricultural Research and Livestock Organisation, Embu, with each going at between Sh200 and Sh300 each.Soursop fruits, according to him, have several nutritional benefits that include keeping cancer at bay, improving eye health, relieving arthritis and help in maintaining good health of liver and kidney.He intends to add many rarer fruits like Kiwano, Durian and Mangosteen on his farm to provide different tastes, nutrients and varieties to the local market. Patrick Gichunge is passionate about growing fruits, but he does not farm the common types that you are likely to find at every dinner table.
On his family’s two acres in Mitunguu, Meru County, he grows atemoya – a hybrid of sugar apple and custard apple, soursop and jack fruits.
“I ventured into fruit farming and trade some 10 years ago, investing Sh5,000, after searching for a job in vain,” says the 34-year-old, who studied commerce at Kenyatta University and graduated in 2010.



