Among his favourite fruits is soursop. “It’s native to the tropical regions of America and Caribbean, and has anti-cancer properties,” says Gichunge.
“I developed interest in these fruits due to their medicinal properties after an encounter with a nutritionist when my father was in hospital suffering from prostate cancer. He was advised to use some of them,” recalls the father of one.





The farmer has five sugar apple, 13 atemoya, eight soursop (graviola) , 14 custard apple and five jackfruit trees.
Lack of ready market
He sourced the seedlings from Kenya Agricultural Research and Livestock Organisation, Embu, with each going at between Sh200 and Sh300 each.
One can also extract seeds from the fruits for planting. The seeds are extracted from the pulp, washed and kept for 30 days to six months before being planted. It takes 3-5 years before the first yields are harvested.
After planting with organic manure, the crop should be mulched to conserve moisture in the soil. “Cover the plant with soil and put a 3-inch mulch.
Keep soil moist, but not wet, when the weather is hot, and when weather is cool, reduce watering,” advises the farmer, who also grows bananas farm.
Soursop fruits, according to him, have several nutritional benefits that include keeping cancer at bay, improving eye health, relieving arthritis and help in maintaining good health of liver and kidney.



