“These fruits are also stress-relievers, boost immunity and respiratory system,” says Gichunge, adding they also have a delicious flavour .
Pests such as moths at the larval stage, bugs and diseases like anthracnose and root rot, are some of the challenges one has to overcome. Lack of a ready market is another.
Available market and climate
“I market the fruits in online marketplaces. I am a part-time farmer and a fruits sourcing agent for a number of exporters, who sell to Middle East. I mainly deal with bananas, apple mangoes, Fuerte, Hass avocados and jumbo avocados and purple passion fruits,” says the farmer.
He intends to add many rarer fruits like Kiwano, Durian and Mangosteen on his farm to provide different tastes, nutrients and varieties to the local market.
Gichunge sells a kilo of soursop fruits at Sh200 mainly at City Park and Ngara markets in Nairobi.
Carol Mutua, a specialist from the Department of Crops, Horticulture and Soils, Egerton University, says a farmer should decide on the fruits to grow depending on available market and climate.





“Also consider security of the fruit trees,  drainage of the farm, cost or capital and the returns on the investment and market for the fruits, whether local or export,” she says.



